eastbound in the #2 lane and V2 was westbound in the #1 lane when V1 lost
control, veered left crossing the #2 westbound lane and contacting the front
plane of V2 with its front plane at both vehicles' left-front corners.  V1
reached maximum engagement at its LF wheel and continued down the left side of
V2 in a side-swipe manner while V2 rotated counter-clockwise more than
180-degrees, departed the westbound road edge, and rolled up onto the embankment
with the left side then slid backward to its final rest position on its left
side but not 90 degrees to code a rollover, pointing southeast.  After
separation, V1 rotated counter-clockwise to final rest in the #1 westbound lane
facing southwest.    Both vehicles were towed due to damage.    The driver and
front-right passenger of V1 were not injured.    The driver, Occupant #4 and
Occupant #5 of V2 were transported and released after treatment of injuries at a
local hospital.
This crash took place on a two lane asphalt constructed highway that runs east
and west.  At the time of the crash it was snowing and the roadway was wet and
slushy.  In the area of the crash there is a curve to the right.  V1 was
traveling east and as V1 came around the curve it started sliding, the driver
down shifted to slow down, but departed the left side of the roadway and
traveled down a steep embankment.  V1 struck a tree with the front plane, then
an embedded rock and part of the tree with the left plane then a second tree
with the front and right planes before coming to final rest at the bottom of the
embankment facing south.    Occupant of V1 was not injured.     V1 was towed
due to damage.
This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, dirt roadway.  In the area
of the crash, the roadway was uphill, exiting a wash that crossed the roadway
and curving right for westbound travel.  At the time of the crash, it was dawn
with no adverse weather conditions.    V1 was westbound, when it steered right
off the road edge, climbed a dirt berme, steered left, tripped and rolled right
an unknown number of times, coming to rest on an unknown plane.    Vehicle #1
was towed due to damage.    The driver, and sole occupant, was transported and
released for her injuries.
This three-vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural
highway with paved shoulders and a guardrail on the northbound road edge.  At
the time of the crash, the weather was clear, it was daylight and there were no
adverse roadway conditions.  In the area of the crash, the roadway was curving
right and downhill for southbound traffic.      V1 was southbound, V2 was
northbound pulling a tandem axle utility trailer and V3 was northbound following
V2 when V1 approached southbound in the northbound lane.  V2 took evasive
action, steering toward the right road edge, but did not contact the guardrail
as V1 steered back to its right and the front plane of V1 contacted the front
plane of V2, then continued down V2's left side, contacted the front-left wheel
of V2's trailer.  V1 then entered a counter-clockwise yaw and contacted the
guardrail on the northbound road edge with its front plane, then came to a stop
across the fog line facing the guardrail.  V2 came to final rest in the
northbound lane facing north-northwest.    Upon approaching the events between
V1 and V2, the V3 driver braked and steered right, but was unable to avoid front
contact to the right plane of V1, causing V1 to rotate counter-clockwise to its
final rest position in the northbound lane facing northeast.  V3 came to rest
in the northbound lane facing north-northeast.    V1 and V2 were towed due to
damage.  V3 was driven from the scene.    The driver of V1 was transported and
release for injuries received.  The FR passenger of V2 was transported and
admitted to control premature labor.
This crash took place on an asphalt constructed highway at a 4-way intersection.
There are two eastbound and three westbound travel lanes and a 2-way center
turn lane.  One of the three westbound lanes is a right turn only lane.   V2 was
stopped in the number three westbound lane.  V1 was travelling west in the
number three lane.  The front plane of V1 struck the rear plane of V2.    V1 was
towed due to damage.  V2 was not towed.    There were no injuries.
This crash took place on an east west two-lane asphalt constructed highway.  At
the time of the crash it was snowing and there was snow on the roadway.  V1 was
traveling east, entered a clockwise rotation, and slid into the westbound lane.
V2 was westbound and the front plane of V2 struck the left plane of V1.  After
impact with V2, V1 yawed counterclockwise and came to rest in the eastbound lane
facing generally south.  V2 came to rest in its original travel lane on
approximate original heading.    Both vehicles were towed due to damage.
Occupants of V2 were transported to a medical facility from the scene.
This crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt constructed residential street.  In
the area of the crash, the roadway "Y's" with a secondary road angling to the
left.  The angling roadway has a steep slope on the right road edge;  all roads
are straight.  At the time of the crash, it was dark with no supplemental
lighting and no adverse weather conditions.    V1 was traveling south and
attempted to veer left onto the angled roadway,  but departed the right road
edge and went down the embankment, contacting a dirt mound with its front plane,
while still moving, V1 contacted a garage with its right side and roof side
rail, then continued until it came to rest with its front plane against  some
rocks in the yard.    V1 was towed due to damage.    Driver was transported and
released.
V1 was traveling westbound and traversing an intersection.  V2 was parked facing
eastbound along north curb on the other side of the intersection.  As V1 passed
through the intersection, the undercarriage of V1 impacted a drainage channel
dip, causing V1 to become briefly airborne and damaging the front suspension.
V1 landed and continued forward, where the front of V1 contacted the front of V2
in a sideswipe-type impact.
This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural
highway as it passed through a small community.  In the area of the crash, the
roadway was level, dry and curving sharply to the left.  At the time of the
crash, it was dark with no adverse weather or roadway conditions.    V1 was
eastbound, negotiating a curve left, entered a counter-clockwise yaw, departed
the road to the right, struck 2 small delineator posts with the right plane,
tripped over and rolled right a total of 6 quarter turns, contacted a small tree
and a barbed wire fence while rolling over, and came to rest on its roof.  All
three occupants were ejected during the roll-over event.    V1 was towed due to
damage.    All three occupants were transported to separate medical facilities
for treatment.
This two-vehicle crash took place on a three-lane, asphalt-constructed rural
highway with a two-way center left turn lane, at a "T" intersection with a
secondary road approaching from the west.  In the area of the crash, the highway
was curving left for southbound traffic and the secondary roadway was straight,
approaching the highway at a 10-degree angle to the tangent of the curve.  At
the time of the crash, it was daylight with no adverse weather or roadway
conditions, but there was a semi-truck and trailer parked on the southbound road
edge, north of the intersection.    V1, westbound, entered the highway
intending to turn left and V2 was southbound on the highway, intending to go
straight.  The front plane of V2 contacted the left plane of V1.  The right
front bumper corner of V2 snagged on the lower C pillar of V1.  V1 entered a
counter-clockwise rotation, exited the roadway, and came to rest on the
northbound shoulder facing south.  V2 was redirected to the southeast, departed
the road to the left, and came to rest on the northbound shoulder, facing west.
Both vehicles were towed due to damage.    The driver of V1, FR passenger of
V1 and both occupants of V2 were transported for their injuries.  The driver of
V1 was hospitalized with a fractured pelvis, and the FR passenger, Occ. #2, of
V2 was admitted for a fractured right femur.  All other occupants were treated
and released.
This two vehicle crash took place on an east/west highway with two travel lanes
in each direction and a two-way center left turn lane.  The intersection is not
controlled for east or westbound traffic, but there are stop signs for north and
southbound traffic.  The highway is asphalt constructed and in the area of the
crash the roadway is level.   At the time of the crash there were no adverse
weather conditions.    V1 was eastbound in the number two lane, when its front
plane contacted the right side of V2, which was southbound crossing the highway,
breaking off the right front wheel of V2. After impact V1 rotated clockwise V2
rotated counter-clockwise and the left side of V1 and the right side of V2 had a
side slap event.  Both vehicles came to final rest southeast of the initial
point of impact; V1 facing generally east and V2 facing generally south.    Both
vehicles were towed due to damage.    The driver of V1 was transported and
released.
This crash took place on a two-lane north/south center striped asphalt
constructed highway in a section which is a transition area into a divided
highway.  In the area of the crash the highway is straight and level.  At the
time of the crash the roadway was dry and there were no adverse weather
conditions.    V1 was northbound and departed the west edge of the roadway, then
re-entered the road in a counterclockwise rotation as a result of steering
input.   V1 crossed the road, then departed the east edge of the roadway, dug
into the dirt shoulder, tripped and rolled right a total of 4 quarter turns and
struck a small tree during the rollover event.  V1 came to rest on a large
mesquite tree facing south.     V1 was towed due to damage.    V1 was
transported and hospitalized.
Vehicle one (V1) was stopped northbound in lane one. Vehicle two (V2) was
westbound in lane two. V1 entered the intersection and the right side was struck
by the front of V2. The vehicles rotated and the right side of V1 struck the
left side of V2. Both vehicles were towed due to damage.
This crash took place on a two-lane east west asphalt constructed highway.  At
the time of the crash it was daylight with no adverse weather conditions.  In
the area of the crash the roadway is straight and level.   V1 was traveling west
when a deer entered the roadway from the right and the front of V1 struck the
deer.  V1 came to final rest on the north shoulder facing generally west.    V1
was towed due to front end damage.
This crash took place on an asphalt constructed roadway at the intersection of a
north and south three lane roadway and a three lane east and west roadway. The
intersection is controlled by a stop sign for north and south bound traffic and
there is no traffic control for east and westbound traffic.  In the area of the
crash there is an eastbound down hill slope.  At the time of the crash the
roadway was dry with no adverse weather conditions.    V1 was traveling north
and had stopped at the intersection.  V2 was eastbound and entered the
intersection intending to go straight.  V1 entered the intersection intending to
go straight, and the front of V2 and the left plane of V1 collided.  After
impact V1 spun in a clockwise direction coming to final rest facing west in the
eastbound lane.  V2 came to final rest in a yard on the southwest corner of the
intersection.    Both vehicles were towed due to damage.    Driver of V1 was
transported and released.
V1 was traveling eastbound in the first lane of a two-lane, two-way roadway,
curving right.  V1 lost traction around the curve and rotated clockwise.  V1
departed the road to the right, where the left side of V1 impacted the
guardrail.
V1 was westbound in the two-way left turn lane of a five-lane roadway, about to
turn left into a private lot.  V2 was traveling eastbound in the second lane of
opposing traffic.  As V1 turned, the front of V1 impacted the front of V2.
This crash took place on a three-lane with a center left turn lane, apshalt
constructed east west highway. In the area of the crash the roadway is level and
straight.  At the time of the crash it was dark with no adverse weather
conditions.    V1 was traveling westbound, drifted left into the eastbound lane,
then departed the road to the left, side swiped a palm tree with the left
plane, snagged on the left C-pillar, entered a counterclockwise rotation, and
came to final rest facing generally north.  There was an oncoming vehicle who
reported to police that he was eastbound and swerved to avoid V1, but there was
not a damage producing event with that vehicle, and no further information other
than the driver's statement.    V1 was towed due to damage.    V1 driver was
transported and hospitalized for observation.
V1 was traveling southbound and exiting a private drive to turn left onto a
two-way street.  V2, a motorcycle, was traveling westbound in the second lane of
the five-lane street, approaching the private drive on its right.  As V1
turned, the motorcycle driver laid the vehicle down on its side attempting to
stop.  The motorcycle slid into the front of V1.
This crash took place on three lane north and south highway with two lanes
southbound and one lane northbound.  In the area of the crash the roadway was
uphill.  At the time of the crash the roadway was dry with no adverse weather
conditions.    V1 was traveling southbound in the number one lane when he
departed the right road side striking an embankment with the front plane causing
V1 to roll one quarter turn on to its right side coming to final rest facing
south.    V1 was towed due to damage.    Driver and occupant were treated at
scene.
V1 entered the roadway from the south road intending to turn left and the front
right corner contacted the left side of V2 .  V1 rotated counter-clockwise and
came to rest in the number two lane facing generally west.  V2, after impact
with V1, entered a counterclockwise rotation, crossing over the center median
divider into eastbound lanes, and the right side of V2 and front plane of V3
collided.  V2 departed this impact in a clockwise rotation and the right side of
V2 and right side of V3 side slapped, then V2 came to rest on the south side of
the roadway facing generally northwest.  After the impacts with V2, V3 came to
final rest facing generally southeast.    V1 was not towed due to damage.  V2
and V3 were towed due to damage.
This two-vehicle crash took place on a five-lane, asphalt-constructed east-west
highway at a driveway on the south side of the highway.  At the time of the
crash, it was daylight with no adverse weather or roadway conditions.  In the
area of the crash, the highway was downhill and straight for eastbound traffic.
V1 was exiting the business, turning left and V2 was eastbound in lane two
when the front of V2 struck the left plane of V1.  After impact, V2 rotated
counter-clockwise and came to rest in the left turn lane facing northeast and V1
rotated clockwise and came to rest farther east in the left turn lane facing
northeast.    Both vehicles were towed due to damage.    The front-right
passenger of V2 was transported and released for neck and head injuries.
This two-vehicle crash took place on the southbound lanes of a four-lane,
asphalt-constructed divided highway with an extended earthen median.  At the
time of the crash, it was daylight with no adverse weather or roadway
conditions.  In the area of the crash, the southbound lanes were downhill and
straight, after exiting a right curve prior to the crash area.    V1 was
southbound in the #1 lane and V2 was southbound in the #2 lane, overtaking V1.
V1 departed the right road edge, corrected to the left, crossed the lane divider
line and contacted the right side of V2 with its left side plane.  The V1
driver then steered right, and V1 entered a clockwise yaw, departed the right
road edge and contacted a cutback embankment with its front plane, tripped over
and rolled left two quarter turns, then slid on its roof and came to rest facing
northeast across both southbound lanes.  V2 continued down the roadway and
parked.  V1 was towed due to damage, V2 was not towed.    The front-middle, and
both rear seat passengers of V1 were transported and released for injuries.
V1's driver and front-right passenger were not injured.    The driver of V2 was
not injured in this crash.      In V1, the driver, right-front passenger and
left-rear passenger all refused transport.  The front-middle and rear-middle
occupants were both transported and released for injuries.    The driver of V2
was uninjured.
This crash took place on two-lane north and south chip sealed roadway.  In the
area of the crash there is a slight downgrade slope with bumps and potholes in
both directions.  At the time of the crash it was dark with no adverse weather
conditions.    V1 was traveling north and drifted off the left side of the
roadway.  The V1 driver apparently steered right, V1 entered a clockwise
rotation, tripped over, and rolled left an unknown number of quarter turns, then
came to rest on the driver side in a ditch located off the right (east) side of
the road, and came to final rest facing generally south.    V1 was towed due to
damage.    Driver of V1 was transported and hospitalized.    Friends took
occupant number two to a medical facility later.
V1 was traveling northbound on a two-lane road curving right.  V1 lost traction
around the curve and rotated clockwise. V1 corrected left and rotated
counter-clockwise.  V1 departed the left side of the road and impacted a
drainage culvert with its front.
This crash took place on a 4-lane asphalt constructed north south roadway.   In
the area of the crash there is a t-intersection controlled by a stop sign.  At
the time of the crash the roadway was dry with no adverse weather conditions.
V2 was facing north, stopped in the left turn lane attempting to make a left
turn when V1 contacted the back plane with its front plane.  Vehicles were
locked together at the bumper; V2 pulled V1 across the intersection to final
rest.    The tow company separated V1 and V2, but did not tow either vehicle
from the crash scene.  The PAR listed V1 as disabled.    There were no injuries.
This crash took place on four-lane, divided highway with an extended grass
median.  In the area of the crash, the westbound lanes were level and curved to
the right.  At the time of the crash, it was dark with no adverse weather
conditions.    V1 was westbound in the #1 lane (DPS numbers them opposite of us)
when it contacted an elk with its front plane, windshield and left side plane.
V1 came to rest after the crash in the westbound lanes, but a passer-by towed
V1 backward onto the westbound shoulder to clear traffic lanes.    V1 was towed
due to damage.    The V1 was transported by air and hospitalized; the right
front seat passenger was transported and released.
This crash took place on a 3-lane asphalt constructed east west highway, two
lanes for westbound traffic and one lane for eastbound traffic.  In the area of
the crash the roadway is curved right with a 2% downhill grade.  At the time of
the crash it was dark with no adverse weather conditions.    V1 and V2 were both
eastbound when an emergency vehicle was approaching.  Traffic moved over to the
right to let the emergency vehicle pass.  After the emergency vehicle passed V1
was attempting to move back into traffic, V2 was ahead of V1 and had not
started moving with traffic.  V1 contacted the back plane of V2 with the front
plane.    V1 was towed due to damage.  V2 was not towed due to damage. No one
was transported for injuries.
This crash took place on a two-lane east west asphalt constructed highway.  In
the area of the crash the roadway is level.  At the time of the crash the
roadway was wet/slushy and it was raining and hailing.    Vehicle one (V1) was
southbound in lane one. The driver of V1 tried to slow down and V1 slid off the
roadway on the left side. The left front tire/wheel struck a ditch and then the
right front tire/wheel struck a culvert. V1 then rolled over to the right two
quarter-turns. V1 was towed due to damage.
This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural
highway oriented north-to-south.  In the area of the crash, the roadway was
curving left and downhill for northbound travel.  At the time of the crash, it
was dark with no adverse weather conditions.    The front plane of V1 contacted
a bull elk, then came to a controlled stop on the right shoulder.    V1 was
towed due to damage.    The driver was not injured.
V1 was traveling northbound in the first lane of a two-lane highway, curving
left.  V1 drifted off the right road edge, correct left and lost control.  V1
crossed the road and departed the road to the left side, where V1 traveling down
a steep embankment and impacted (frontally) the ground at the bottom.  V1
rolled two quarter-turns towards its right side and came to rest on its top.
V1 was traveling westbound around a rightward curve.  A bull elk entered the
road; the front of V1 impacted the elk.
V1 was traveling westbound in the first lane of a two-lane roadway, curving
left.  V1 departed the right road edge, correct left, and lost traction.  V1
rotated counter-clockwise as it departed the left roadside and impacted a rock
embankment with its front.  V1 continued rotating and impacted the embankment
again with its right side.
This crash took place in the southbound lanes of a 4-lane divided highway with
an extended grass median. In the area of the crash the roadway is straight with
a 2% downgrade.  At the time of the crash the roadway was dry, it was daylight
and there were no adverse weather conditions.    V1 was traveling south when it
swerved to the right to miss an animal in the road, V1 departed the right road
edge, re-entered and crossed the road, then departed the road to the left,
contacted 2 small desert trees with its left plane, then a ditch with the front
plane, then tripped over and rolled two-quarter turns to the left before coming
to rest on its top facing the roadway.    V1 was towed due to damage.    The
driver of V1 was transported and released.
This two-vehicle crash took place on a 6-lane, asphalt-constructed highway at a
shopping center entrance, which was controlled by a traffic light having a turn
only arrow for westbound left turns.  In the area of the crash, the roadway to
the west of the intersection, the eastbound lanes, had a right turn bay into the
shopping center and curved slightly left for westbound traffic.  The roadway to
the east of the intersection was straight and level with a right turn bay for
eastbound traffic.  At the time of the crash, it was daylight with no adverse
weather or roadway conditions.    Vehicle #1 was eastbound in the #1 travel lane
and Vehicle #2 was westbound, turning left into the shopping center parking lot
when the front of V2 contacted the left side of V1.  V1 continued east and came
to rest in the right turn lane on the east side of the intersection and V2
rotated counter-clockwise and came to rest in the intersection facing southeast.
Both vehicles were towed due to damage.    The drivers of both vehicles were
transported by air ambulance for perceived serious injuries.  All other
occupants of V1 were transported and released for minor injuries
This crash took place on a three-lane north south asphalt constructed highway
with a depressed median dividing northbound and southbound lanes.  There is one
lane for northbound traffic.  In the area of the crash the roadway is level.  At
the time of the crash it was dark and the road was not illuminated by
streetlights.      V1 was traveling north and apparently was struck from behind
on the back right corner by a , departed the left side of the road down into the
depressed dirt median, and contacted a barrier composed of dirt and fence
material, then a sewer grate and group of large rocks at the bottom of the
embankment, all with the front plane.      V1 was towed due to damage.    Driver
was not transported from scene although he went to the emergency room on his
own.
This crash took place at a four-way intersection controlled with a red, yellow
and green stoplight.  V1 was traveling westbound; V2 was southbound attempting
to make a left hand turn at the intersection.  V2 proceeded through the
intersection turning left when V1 crossed through the intersection striking the
left rear plane of V2 with its front plane.  After impact both vehicles rotated
counter-clockwise 180 degrees before coming to final rest.    Both vehicles were
towed due to damage. V2 occupant 1 was transported and released.
V1 was traveling westbound and passing through an intersection.  V2 was
traveling southbound and passing through the same intersection.  In the
intersection, the front of V2 impacted the right side of V1.
This single vehicle rollover took place on a two-lane, graded, dirt/gravel
roadway.  In the area of the crash, the roadway was level and curved sharply
right for southbound traffic.  At the time of the crash, it was daylight with no
adverse weather conditions and the roadway was reported to have a "washboard"
surface from wear and erosion.    V1 was southbound, negotiating a right hand
curve when it entered a clockwise rotation, departed the right road edge,
tripped and rolled left three-quarter turns, then came to rest on its right side
facing north, with part of its rear end in the southbound lane.    V1 was towed
due to damage.    Neither occupant reported any injuries.
This crash took place on a two-lane asphalt constructed highway with a center
turn lane.  At the beginning of the crash area the roadway is curved to the
left.  The roadway has a 2% downhill slope.  At the time of the crash it was
daylight with some cloudiness and the roadway was dry.    V1 was traveling
southbound, departed the road to the right down an embankment rotated counter
clockwise, struck a tree with the right plane, tripped over, rolled right 1
quarter turn.  The rollover was interrupted by impact to large tree with the top
plane.  V1 came to rest on its right side against the tree.    V1 was towed due
to damage.
This crash took place on a two-lane east west asphalt constructed highway.  In
the area of the crash the roadway was level.  At the time of the crash it was
daylight with no adverse weather conditions.    V2, a class A motor home, was
traveling eastbound pulling a boat and trailer; V1 was traveling eastbound
behind V2.  V2 was slowing down as a third vehicle which was not involved was
pulling off to the right road edge, V2 was attempting to move past this vehicle
when the outboard boat motor was struck from behind by the front plane of V1.
V1 was towed due to damage.    The outboard boat motor from V2 was
disassembled from the boat and was left at a nearby marina.  No other damage was
apparent to V2 or the boat trailer.    There were no reported injuries.
V1 was stopped facing westbound on the right roadside in the bike lane of an
otherwise two-lane roadway, intending to make a U-turn.  V2 was behind V1 in the
first westbound lane.  As V1 executed the turn, the front of V2 impacted the
left side of V1.
V1 was traveling northbound on a two-lane road and curving let.  V1 departed the
road to the right in a counter-clockwise yaw.  V1 impacted a boulder with its
right side and continued forward.  V1's front knocked a signpost down, and then
impacted the right rail-guard of a bridge.  V1 broke through the rail-guard and
vaulted over the right side of the bridge.  V1 overturned as it fell and
contacted the rock riverbank with its top.  V1 continued to fall and landed on
its top in the river, submerged.
This crash took place on a two-lane, striped centerline east west asphalt
constructed highway.  In the area of the crash the road is divided by a painted
yellow double line.  The collision occurred in a curved portion of the roadway,
which sweeps to the right for westbound traffic.  At the time of the crash it
was daylight with no adverse weather conditions.    V1 was traveling westbound,
traveled left of the centerline where the front plane contacted the front plane
of V2, which was traveling eastbound.  After impact V1 rotated clockwise 90
degrees and came to rest in the eastbound lane facing north.  V2 rotated
clockwise 90 degrees and came to rest on the shoulder of the westbound lane
facing south.    Both vehicles were towed due to damage.      Driver of V1 was
fatally injured.    Driver and passengers of V2 were transported to separate
medical facilities.
This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed rural
roadway at a bridge across a dry creek bed.  At the time of the crash, it was
dark with no adverse weather or roadway conditions.  In the area of the crash,
the roadway was level and curving left for southbound traffic.    Vehicle 1 (V1)
was southbound when it departed the right road edge, prior to the bridge,
yawing counterclockwise.  As it departed the road, V1 struck a culvert sign on
the right road edge then rolled right one-quarter turn coming to rest on its
right side in the creek bed.    V1 was towed due to damage.
V1 was traveling eastbound and approaching an intersection to turn left.  V1
turned left at the intersection onto a north-south roadway, but continued
turning and departed the road to the left side, where the front of V1 struck a
ditch and a wall, bringing V1 to rest.
This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural
highway.  At the time of the crash, it was dark with rain falling.  In the area
of the crash, the roadway was straight, level and wet from rain.    V1 was
eastbound when the driver related she heard a loud noise from the Left Front
tire, and the vehicle departed the left road edge, descended a gentle grade and
impacted a barbed wire fence with its front and left planes.  Some of the
fencing material scratched the paint on the right side of the vehicle before it
came to final rest halfway through the fencerow, facing east. The tire was
damaged in the crash and was part of the vehicle that impacted the ditch so
prior damage to the tire was not determined.     V1 was towed from the scene.
The driver and sole occupant of V1 was not injured.
Vehicle one (V1) was negotiating a left curved two-lane dirt roadway.  V1
departed the left side of the road in a clckwise yaw.  While returning to the
road V1 began to rollover to its left side.  V1 rolled three 1/4 turns and came
to rest off the right side of the road.
This two-vehicle crash took place at a driveway entrance onto a five-lane,
asphalt-constructed rural highway.  In the area of the crash, the highway was
downhill and curving right for eastbound traffic.  At the time of the crash,
weather was cloudy with rain imminent, it was daylight and there were no adverse
roadway conditions.    V1 was exiting a business on the south side of the
highway, turning west; V2 was eastbound in the #1 lane.  V2 changed lanes to
avoid V1, but was unsuccessful, contacting the left side of V1 with its front
plane.  V2 came to rest in the center left-turn lane facing eastbound; V1
rotated almost 90-degrees clockwise and came to rest in the #2 eastbound lane.
This crash took place on a three lane roadway which consists of two northbound

quarter turns down an embankment and over a fence before coming to final rest on

This two-vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed rural

V1 was southbound, following a non-contact vehicle and V2 was northbound; V1

V1 was eastbound and V2 was westbound pulling a large travel-trailer on a rural

to a stop on the westbound shoulder facing northwest.
This crash took place on a two-lane east west asphalt constructed highway.  In

V1 was traveling westbound when it went left into the oncoming lane, departed

V1 then re-entered the roadway, tripped and rolled right 2 quarter turns,and

This crash took place at a four-way intersection with a center turn lane for

V1 was traveling westbound and was approaching the intersection.  The left front
plane of V1 contacted the right rear plane of V2.
This 3-vehicle crash took place at a 4-way intersection.  The westbound lanes

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural

This single vehicle crash took place on the westbound lanes of a rural,

V1 was in the #2 lane when an elk entered from the left.  V1 was steered right,

This two-vehicle crash took place in a light controlled four-way intersection.
V1 entered the intersection from the west with intentions of turning left.  V2

direction.
This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural

This single vehicle crash took place on the northbound lanes of a four-lane,

This single vehicle rollover crash took place on a two-lane,

This single vehicle rollover crash took place on the southbound lanes of a

This crash took place on a two-lane asphalt constructed north south highway.  In

This crash took place in the northbound lanes of a four lane highway with an

This three-vehicle crash took place on a six-lane, asphalt-constructed highway

This crash took place on a two-lane northbound asphalt constructed highway.  In

This two-vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed rural

This crash took place on a two-lane north south asphalt constructed highway.  In

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural

V1 was westbound, crossed the northbound lanes and the median area of a

This crash took place on the two northbound lanes of a four-lane divided

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural

This crash took place on a two-lane asphalt constructed north south roadway.  In

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural

This crash took place on a two-lane asphalt constructed east west roadway.  In

This crash took place on a two-lane asphalt constructed east west highway.  In

This single-vehicle crash took place on the southbound lanes of a four-lane,

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed street

This crash took place on a two-lane rural asphalt constructed roadway. In the

This crash took place on a two-lane asphalt constructed east west highway.  In

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed city

This two-vehicle crash took place on a five-lane, asphalt-constructed highway

This single vehicle crash took place on a two-lane, asphalt-constructed, rural
